  9  /-!
 10  
 11  A tactic for discharging linear arithmetic goals using Fourier-Motzkin elimination.
 12  
 13  `linarith` is (in principle) complete for ℚ and ℝ. It is not complete for non-dense orders, i.e. ℤ.
 14  
 15  @TODO: investigate storing comparisons in a list instead of a set, for possible efficiency gains
 16  @TODO: delay proofs of denominator normalization and nat casting until after contradiction is found
 17  -/
 18  
 19  meta def nat.to_pexpr : ℕ → pexpr
id                           ┴ ┴ └───┘
src                          ┴   └───┘
typ                          ┴ ┴ └───┘
doc                              └───┘
 20  | 0 := ``(0)
 21  | 1 := ``(1)
 22  | n := if n % 2 = 0 then ``(bit0 %%(nat.to_pexpr (n/2))) else ``(bit1 %%(nat.to_pexpr (n/2)))

125  /--
126    The main datatype for FM elimination.
127    Variables are represented by natural numbers, each of which has an integer coefficient.
128    Index 0 is reserved for constants, i.e. `coeffs.find 0` is the coefficient of 1.
129    The represented term is coeffs.keys.sum (λ i, coeffs.find i * Var[i]).
130    str determines the direction of the comparison -- is it < 0, ≤ 0, or = 0?

806  /--
807    Tries to prove a goal of `false` by linear arithmetic on hypotheses.
808    If the goal is a linear (in)equality, tries to prove it by contradiction.
809    If the goal is not `false` or an inequality, applies `exfalso` and tries linarith on the
810    hypotheses.
811    `linarith` will use all relevant hypotheses in the local context.
812    `linarith [t1, t2, t3]` will add proof terms t1, t2, t3 to the local context.
813    `linarith only [h1, h2, h3, t1, t2, t3]` will use only the goal (if relevant), local hypotheses
814      h1, h2, h3, and proofs t1, t2, t3. It will ignore the rest of the local context.
815    `linarith!` will use a stronger reducibility setting to identify atoms.
816  
817    Config options:
818    `linarith {exfalso := ff}` will fail on a goal that is neither an inequality nor `false`
819    `linarith {restrict_type := T}` will run only on hypotheses that are inequalities over `T`
820    `linarith {discharger := tac}` will use `tac` instead of `ring` for normalization.
821      Options: `ring2`, `ring SOP`, `simp`
822  -/
